   9: The configuration file is not automatically created; you can create it using your favorite plain-text editor. By default, centd(1) will look for a file named cent.conf(5) in the cent data directory, but both the data directory and the configuration file path may be changed using the '\-datadir' and '\-conf' command-line arguments.
  11: cent.conf should be located in $HOME/.cent
  16: Enable or disable run on the test network instead of the real *cent* network.
  32: Tells *cent* to accept or not accept JSON-RPC commands.
  47: You can use *cent* or *centd(1)* to send commands to *cent*/*centd(1)* running on another host using this option.
  50: Use Secure Sockets Layer (also known as TLS or HTTPS) to communicate with *cent* '\-server' or *centd(1)*. Example of OpenSSL settings used when *rpcssl*='1':
